Pharyngoconjunctival fever, commonly caused by adenovirus, is a viral infection characterized by fever, sore throat, and conjunctivitis. The global market for pharyngoconjunctival fever can be segmented based on virus type, diagnosis, and treatment. In terms of virus type, adenovirus is the primary cause, but other respiratory viruses can also lead to this condition. When it comes to diagnosis, healthcare providers rely on clinical symptoms such as throat pain and redness in the eyes, as well as laboratory testing for confirmation. Regarding treatment, management usually involves providing symptomatic relief such as pain medications and eye drops, although antiviral medications may be considered in severe cases.

